Persuasive messages live largely unexplored "social lives". Within rich information environments, each message interacts and competes with its "peers", that is other messages which are relevant to the same attitude or behavior and which may (not) be congruent with the focal message (\cite{hendriks_social_2018, stautz_immediate_2016, young_effectiveness_2018, scholz_neural_2019}). These interactions likely create interference between message effects and, thereby, complicate the prediction of message effectiveness. For instance, like most daily choices, alcohol consumption has pros and cons. It is a social catalyst, associated with fun and friendship (\cite{duckworth_transitions_2021}), but also a significant cause of death, injury, and disease (\cite{oecd_avoidable_2016}). In line with this ambiguity, diverse stakeholders, from alcohol brands, to public health officials, to party-loving peers and concerned family, seek to influence alcohol consumption. Their voices create rich information environment and frequent exposures to alcohol-related messages varying in valence (pro/anti-alcohol) and source (peers or professionals). Extensive prior work has examined individual message types (e.g. exclusively pro-; \cite{jernigan_alcohol_2017} or anti-alcohol messages; \cite{young_effectiveness_2018}). Yet, we know little about how the effects of messages varying in source and valence compare to and potentially interfere with one another. Across three exploratory studies, we directly compare effects of diverse alcohol-related messages on alcohol craving and ask whether these messages exert their influence through similar or different psychological mechanisms. 

\subsection{Persuasion in Complex Information Environments}

How do people make decisions in complex, ambiguous information environments such as that surrounding alcohol? The human brain is capable of seamlessly and speedily weighting myriad factors relevant to a given decision (\cite{busemeyer_cognitive_2019}). This is reflected in behavior change and decision-making theories like the Reasoned Action Approach (\cite{fishbein_predicting_2010}) and Identity-Value Model (\cite{berkman_finding_2017}), which describe an integration process where diverse information relevant to a given choice (e.g. social norms and attitudes) is integrated and weighed to inform a decision (\cite{levy_comparing_2011, falk_persuasion_2018}). In other words, when deciding whether to consume alcohol, individuals likely consider multiple alcohol information types, such as both pro- and anti-alcohol information from peers and professionals. Modern information environments like social media further make it more likely that diverse information about alcohol is encountered in close spatial and temporal proximity and, thus, similarly salient at the time of decision-making.

One small aspect of this integration process has been studied fruitfully in communication research on the interactions between mass media messages and message-related interpersonal communication. The Two-Step Flow model (\cite{katz_two-step_1957, katz_personal_1955}) posits that mass media influences target groups indirectly through the gate-keeping efforts of \textit{opinion leaders} who further distribute and interpret messages within their social network. Empirical evidence shows that message-related interpersonal communication impacts both who is exposed to mass media content and how message receivers are affected (\cite{southwell_roles_2007, jeong_effect_2017}). This can result in either enhanced (\cite{van_den_putte_interpersonal_2011}) or diminished (\cite{david_social_2006}) message effects. Research on alcohol consumption similarly shows that the effects of anti-alcohol messaging are partially mediated by the valence (pro- or anti-alcohol) of subsequent interpersonal conversations (e.g. \cite{hendriks_talking_2012}), and the extent to which daily drinking decisions are unhealthily impacted by pro-alcohol interpersonal conversations depends partially on an individual's sensitivity to anti-alcohol persuasive messaging (\cite{scholz_neural_2019}).

This work highlights the importance and potential contributions of research into the social life of persuasive messaging, but only considers one specific type of message interactions. The broader persuasion literature remains split into disconnected fields, each focusing on individual message types. For instance, research on social influences on alcohol consumption (e.g. \cite{borsari_peer_2001}) rarely intersects with work on professionally produced messaging on the same topic (e.g. \cite{jeong_effect_2017,jernigan_alcohol_2017}), and work on pro-alcohol messages rarely considers anti-alcohol message effects. The result is incomparable data employing diverse operationalizations and theoretical foundations underlying our understanding of message effects. Consequently, we know little about the real-world competition between message types: 

Research Question (RQ)1: What are the relative effects of alcohol-related messages varying in valence and source on alcohol craving?  

\subsection{Competition Across Valence and Source Dimensions}

To answer RQ1, we immersed study participants in rich information environments containing alcohol-related messages varying in valence and source to compare their effects on alcohol craving. Alcohol craving is a key predictor of consumption [CITE RAMIREZ 2014], sensitive to message exposure manipulations [Noel Lakhan 2021, Stautz Marteau 2016], and can ethically and validly be measured on repeated trials. 
 
Although prior work produced mixed results regarding the average effectiveness of pro- and anti-alcohol messages [CITES], the underlying intention behind these message types is to enhance or diminish alcohol craving, respectively. First, we sought to establish whether our message samples achieved this goal: 

H1: Alcohol craving will be higher in response to pro- versus non-alcoholic messages and non-alcoholic versus anti-alcohol messages. 

Message effects as hypothesized in H1 are more consequential for public health interests to the extent that they specifically modulate craving for alcohol as opposed to general appetite for beverages. Prior work is uninformative regarding the specificity of alcohol message effects.

H2: The effect pro- vs. anti-alcohol messaging on is stronger when craving is assessed for alcoholic rather than non-alcoholic beverages. 

After establishing these basic relationships, we can examine novel, relative effects of different message types: To reduce (risky) alcohol consumption, is it more effective to produce more anti-alcohol messaging or further regulate pro-alcohol messaging? To our knowledge, only two existing studies addressed this question, with contradictory results and limited generalizability. Stautz and Marteau (CITE 2016) randomly assigned participants to view either ten anti-alcohol, pro-alcohol, or non-alcoholic video advertisements. Anti-alcohol (vs. non-alcoholic) messages significantly reduced drinking urges, while pro-alcohol stimuli did not have significant effects. Using the same design, Stautz and colleagues (CITE 2017) found consistently (but insignificantly) larger effects in the pro- vs. non-alcoholic compared to the anti- vs. non-alcoholic comparison. It remains unclear how these results translate to new stimulus types or to complex information environments which contain more than one message type per person. The present study compares relative effect sizes of a larger sample of static pro- and anti-alcohol messages (relative to non-alcoholic stimuli) in a within-subject design.

With regards to the effects of message source, both professional and peer-produced alcohol information have been found to impact alcohol consumption and its determinants [CITES}. However, we are not aware of direct comparisons of their effects on alcohol craving or consumption. Are carefully designed campaigns more successful in influencing alcohol craving than relatable peer-produced messages or vice versa? Do source effects differ across pro- and anti-alcohol messages? We extent the limited prior work comparing pro- and anti-alcohol content by including both professionally and peer-produced stimuli.

\subsection{Drivers of Alcohol Craving}

Designing reliable, generalizable message effects requires an understanding of the underlying psychological mechanisms. More specifically, in the context of complex information environments, quantifying the relative importance of a mechanism  for different message types may help to predict the likelihood and nature of interference between their effects. For instance, if both pro- and anti-alcohol messaging affect alcohol consumption by portraying self-relevant circumstances, which of these appeals exerts greater influence? 

RQ2: Is alcohol craving in response to alcohol-related messages varying in valence and source driven by similar or different psychological mechanisms?

We examined RQ2 on the example of two particularly central mechanisms in the context of the alcohol information environment: emotions and familiarity.

\subsubsection{Emotions}
Emotional responses are frequent targets of persuasive messages across behavioral domains (\cite{dillard_affect_2012,poels_role_2019,hornik_quantitative_2016,nabi_emotion_2017}). Similarly, both pro- and anti-alcohol messaging often aim to evoke emotions. One of the few direct comparisons between pro- and anti-alcohol messaging (\cite{stautz_impact_2017}) suggests that:  

H3: Pro-alcohol messages are associated with more positive and less negative emotional responses than anti-alcohol messages.

Professional anti-alcohol messaging often emphasizes negative outcomes of (excessive) consumption such as catastrophic accidents (fear) caused by drunk drivers (shame/guilt) or inappropriate social situations (shame; \cite{becheur_emotions_2007,duhachek_guilt_2012}). In contrast, professional pro-alcohol messaging often highlights positive aspects of alcohol consumption. For instance, partying and relaxation are major themes in US TV advertising for alcohol (\cite{morgenstern_content_2015}). These emotional responses to pro- (\cite{chen_alcohol_2005}) and anti-alcohol [CITE] messaging are known to be related to message effectiveness.

To meaningfully compare emotional mechanisms of message effects between different message types, we focus on emotional responses that are relevant across message types and could, thus, theoretically lead to inferences between message effects. Following the example of prior work (STAUTZ 2017), we thus assessed general positive and negative emotions as opposed to specific emotions. Yet, treating these general measures as mediators of message effects would require the questionable assumption that, for instance, positive emotions associated with different message types are qualitatively similar. Instead, we compare how and how strongly positive and negative emotions are related to craving and how these effects are moderated by message type. Based on prior work, we expect that:

H4: Alcohol craving will be positively associated with positive emotional responses to alcohol-related messages (H4a) and negatively associated with negative emotional responses (H4b). 

Further, we expect that, on average, emotions that are more frequently targeted by a message type will play a larger role in impacting subsequent alcohol craving for this message type.

H5: When comparing pro- to anti-alcohol messages, positive emotional responses will be more strongly (H5a) and negative emotional responses will be less strongly (H5b) associated with craving. 

Most of the existing work on emotional responses to alcohol messages has focused on professional messages. Yet, early content analyses suggest that emotional mechanisms may function differently for peer-produced messaging. Peer-produced messages generally have less clear persuasive intentions (\cite{hendriks_alcohol-related_2017}) and, consequently, employ emotional appeals less consistently and less strategically. While peer-produced pro-alcohol messages generally seem to mimic professional pro-alcohol content in that they often express positive emotions related to alcohol, peer-produced anti-alcohol messages may be more emotionally ambiguous. For instance, a social media post may depict negative outcomes of drinking similar to those displayed in professional anti-alcohol campaigns (e.g. a bike accident), but portray it in a humorous light as the unfortunate, yet funny outcome of an epic night. Such ambiguity is incentivised by the strong pro-alcohol norms among young adults (\cite{beullens_display_2013}). How are these emotions linked to craving? We will explore source effects on this relationship here. 

\subsubsection{Familiarity}
We define familiarity as perceptions that a message shows characters who are 'like me' and/or a familiar situation. The literature discusses these types of familiarity under audience-character similarity (\cite{kim_effect_2016,bochner_effectiveness_1994}) and message self-relevance. Generally, familiarity is viewed as favorable to message effectiveness because it enhances attention and the perceived message relevance. In fact, creating familiar scenarios and characters are popular tailoring strategies that are linked to message effectiveness across domains (\cite{lustria_meta-analysis_2013,noar_does_2007}). Similarly, self-relevance is positively associated with persuasion (for a review see \cite{falk_persuasion_2018}). 

H7: Familiarity will enhance message effectiveness so that familiarity with pro-alcohol messages will be positively associated and familiarity with anti-alcohol messages will be negatively associated with craving. 

Content analyses of alcohol-related posts on social media suggest that pro-alcohol content is much more prevalent than anti-alcohol messages (REFS). More generally, strong pro-alcohol social norms among young adults likely create similar patterns of overexposure to pro- rather than anti-alcohol content through other mediated and interpersonal communication. Moreover, general self-serving biases (\cite{mezulis_is_2004}) and third-person effects [CITE] likely bias recipients of anti-alcohol information to underestimate their own similarities with characters who are experiencing negative outcomes from drinking alcohol. 

H8: Pro-alcohol information will be perceived as more familiar than anti-alcohol information. 

Based on these observations, we hypothesize that message receivers draw less severe consequences when feeling familiar with anti- compared to pro-alcohol content. 

H9: Familiarity will be more strongly linked to alcohol craving for pro- vs. anti-alcohol messages.

Prior work focused on familiarity of professional messaging, creating a knowledge gap about peer-produced messages, which likely have stronger objective similarities with the life of message recipients. Is familiarity a stronger driver of craving in response to peer or professional messages and do these effects differ by message valence?

\section{Method}
We conducted three online experiments to directly compare the impact of different types of alcohol-related messages on alcohol craving and to explore mechanisms of these effects. Study 1a established craving responses to a large sample of professional and peer-produced pro- and anti-alcohol messages. Study 1b further introduced a comparison condition of professional- and peer-produced messages about non-alcoholic beverages. Study 2 conceptually replicated Studies 1a/b using a subset of the same alcoholic stimuli and a slightly different task design. All participants provided informed consent and study procedures were approved by the ethical review board at [UNIVERSITY ANONYMIZED FOR REVIEW] (#2020-PC-12672). All measures are available on our OSF page [LINK].

