\subsection{Messages}
A set of $\Sexpr{length(unique(study1a_drink_df$QualtricsMsgID))}$ alcohol-related ($\Sexpr{study1a_drink_df %>% group_by(condition) %>% summarize(n_msgs=length(unique(QualtricsMsgID))) %>% summarize(first(n_msgs))}$/valence*source condition) and $\Sexpr{study1b_drink_df %>% filter(grepl('non',condition)) %>% summarize(length(unique(QualtricsURL)))}$ non-alcoholic messages (15/source condition) were generated. All stimuli consisted of a still image depicting one or more individuals consuming or holding alcoholic or non-alcoholic drinks and a hashtag. Images were purposefully sampled from public Instagram posts and prior research in order to manipulate valence (pro-/anti-/non-alcoholic) and source (professional/peer). Pro- and anti-alcohol images displayed alcohol or alcohol consumption in a positive or negative light, respectively. Non-alcoholic messages portrayed non-alcoholic beverages and/or their consumption in a positive light. Source was manipulated by sampling images from Instagram pages of businesses (e.g. alcohol brands) and international, English-language anti-(binge) drinking campaings studied in prior research (\cite{scholz_neural_2019}); professional sources) or from public Instagram accounts of 'normal' users (peer sources). Hashtags were manipulated to reinforce image condition (e.g. using brand names, campaign slogans, or hashtags commonly used on Instagram) and to control the amount of text between conditions. For more information, consult the Supplementary Materials.

