Next we used a multi-level regression model to predict craving from message familiarity, message valence and source and relevant two-way interactions, accounting for random intercepts per participant, stimulus, and study. On average, participants reported higher alcohol craving in response to more familiar alcohol messages (main effects model in Table \ref{tab:famTable}). In partial support of H6, this effect was moderated by message valence so that familiarity was more strongly positively associated with alcohol craving in pro- compared to anti-alcohol messages (see full model in Table \ref{tab:famTable}). Unexpectedly, we found an effect strength, not an effect direction moderation. Familiarity did not universally enhance message effectiveness as the effect of familiarity on alcohol craving remained positive in response to anti-alcohol messages. Interestingly, controlling for familiarity revealed a significant effect of stimulus source on craving so that professional sources led to more craving, suggesting that familiarity is a confounder in Table \ref{tab:cravingTableMain}. This points to a paradoxical effect of professional alcohol messaging. On average, it is associated with (insignificantly) less craving than peer-produced messages, but it also is perceived as more familiar than peer-messages, which is, in turn, associated with higher craving.

